DSS.title: Guest Users are not being properly deleted

comments.body:
export data from production on `dss-prod1`
```
mysqldump -h 128.112.200.45 -p -u dss dss_production > dss_production-4-14-2020.sql
gzip dss_production-4-14-2020.sql
mv dss_production-4-14-2020.sql.gz ~
```

start a mysql 5.7 or earlier as pgloader has issues with later versions
```
brew service stop mysql
brew uninstall mysql
rm -rf /usr/local/var/mysql
rm /usr/local/etc/my.cnf
brew install mysql@5.7
brew link --force mysql@5.7
brew services start mysql@5.7
gem uninstall mysql2
gem install mysql2
```

Locally - Change you database.yml dev name to match the server you are targeting `dss-staging` or `dss-production`
```
mysql -u root <target-server> < dss_production-4-14-2020.sql
pgloader mysql://root@localhost/dss_staging postgresql://localhost/dss_staging
```
update your database.yml to have the new postgres connection information

pulfalight.title: Allow requesting of components with level="otherlevel" otherlevel="text"

comments.body:
I believe @faith may have used the word "bug" (`The fact that these items aren't requestable on the current site was deemed to be a bug`) generically to describe that a problem exists, not to identify the bug itself.

In my opinion, changing the data to accommodate existing code is not a good solution. The policy has been that only retrievable physical items can be requestable. @sdellis I worry that what you're suggesting would make non-physical items requestable in the finding aid. That would create a different problem for Public Services, since they're not in fact retrievable, so we'd have to address that issue in the request bundling anyway (we'd have to treat them like folders in a box or something like that). 

If we're going to have to add a scenario anyway, I think it'd be much better to leave the container information on the physical item and add the scenario of non-retrievable othertypes to the code, not change the data to shoehorn it into existing code.

comments.body: While reviewing this with @khanhvu98kk and @sdellis, it was determined that attempting to provide objects (rather than strings) for child container nodes should also be supported in this (or another related PR).

Only the title and the ID is necessary in order to render each individual component. I will work to remove the unneeded attributes.

The nested hierarchy is actually what is valuable here, and the structure alone might have performance impacts for larger EADs.
